1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:15,000
I have to do a little quick introduction.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:23,000
My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Oral History Program.

4
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:28,000
I'm with the videographer John Bishop. We are in St. Augustine, Florida.

5
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:34,000
Today is Tuesday, the 13th of September 2011.

6
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:45,000
We are at the Bayfront Hilton in St. Augustine to do a series of interviews related to local civil rights history for the Civil Rights History Project,

7
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:52,000
which is a joint undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

8
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:59,000
John Bishop, I think we are not recording to the X-T cards.

9
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:03,000
Okay, we have those back. Do you need me room tone?

10
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:07,000
No, we are okay. Any other housekeeping?

11
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:14,000
No, I think not. Okay. We're delighted today to be able to sit down with you, Miss Duncan.

12
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:21,000
Our interviewee is Miss Gwendolyn Annette Perkins Duncan.

13
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:29,000
And we will talk about local civil rights history and her involvements that are ongoing still even today.

14
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Thank you very much for your generous willingness to sit down and also your flexibility, because I know we've had to juggle our day today.

15
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,000
So thank you for that.

16
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:45,000
I can ask you just to, and I think we'll probably spend about a half an hour together so we can kind of pace ourselves that way.

17
00:01:45,000 --> 00:02:02,000
I wonder if you can start by talking a little bit about your family and how it situated here historically in St. Augustine and how you've all had your various involvements in the movement and its legacy.

18
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:15,000
I'll start off. My name is Gwendolyn and I was born and raised in Lincolnville of St. Augustine, Florida, June 28th, 1956.

19
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:28,000
I am a fifth generation native, my great grandfather, my great-great grandfather, Thomas A. Finley, lived in St. Augustine and in Lincolnville.

20
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:42,000
I was told that he moved from the Carolinas. It took many years for them to get here and I used to often wonder from a child, why would they come so far to St. Augustine?

21
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:53,000
What was the driving force to leave this family to come? Finley is a certain name to St. Augustine. And later in life I learned why.

22
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:10,000
But my great-great grandfather had 13 children. Some were born along the way coming to St. Augustine in South Carolina, Georgia, and eventually he ended up in Moultrie, which is just south of St. Augustine, St. John's County.

23
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:24,000
I was told that we did the research that he had about 13 acres and was a farmer. His daughter, which was my great-grandmother, Abby Finley.

24
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:39,000
She married her husband, Abby Finley, and she bought some land in Lincolnville. The St. Augustine record which did not mention black people often made mention of his 89th year old.

25
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:54,000
He died at 89 years of age and they said he served the white community well. That was in the newspaper. We all just said, we were what he was, he brought his wares from Moultrie to St. Augustine, the city of.

26
00:03:54,000 --> 00:04:07,000
And eventually moved in Lincolnville with my great-grandmother. She was a founder of St. Cyprian's and the Episcopal Church, which has been in Lincolnville for maybe over 150 years now.

27
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:20,000
My mother's grandmother, Elizabeth, I know it was Abby. She lived right directly across from the church, which they built.

28
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:30,000
And still, you know, they have a congregation right even to this day. It was fun growing up in Lincolnville. Things were segregated.

29
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:40,000
But, you know, as a child, you really didn't know what segregation was all about until you venture it off in downtown areas.

30
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:47,000
But growing up in Lincolnville, like I said, it was great. There were many businesses along the way because of the segregation.

31
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:56,000
You know, you had your own grocery stores. You had the beauty parlors. There were bars along the street on Washington Street.

32
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:07,000
There were, had newspaper publishers. You know, everything you need it was in Lincolnville. And the church was a center of activity.

33
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:17,000
They had the church socials, picnics, everything centered around the church. And I am one of eight girls. My mother had eight girls, no boys.

34
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:30,000
And so I guess it was kind of, you know, the house was situated for women. And young girls, not my stepfather, who was only a man in the house, but a hard working man.

35
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:37,000
And I thank the Lord, you know, for my great grandmother. I knew her. She died at probably about 89 or 90 years of age as well.

36
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:49,000
She died before my grandmother, my mother's mother died. And she died in November of 1963. Same month that President Kennedy was shot. I can remember that happening.

37
00:05:49,000 --> 00:06:02,000
But I know you want to talk about the civil rights movement. What I remember most from a child at seven and a half years old when Dr. King came to St. Augustine was the marches by the Ku Klux Klan.

38
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:09,000
From a child's point of view, every dress through Lincolnville, from a child's point of view, and you didn't know what was happening.

39
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:16,000
You thought it was some big parade that you wanted to participate in. You know, it was just, you know, it was a parade to me.

40
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:28,000
But I can recall, you know, at night, there was a time of terror. And I remember one night in particular, I guess all the black people came out.

41
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:35,000
I was a little child, but I can remember, you know, black people lining the streets in the Ku Klux Klan marching through the area.

42
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:47,000
And we went down on the corner of the Haven in Central Avenue, which is now Martin Luther King Avenue. And we watched the marches march through our area.

43
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:55,000
And I can remember, as we were walking home, my mom holding my sister's hands in mine, and she said, don't look back.

44
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:08,000
I could just remember the terror of don't look back. Keep walking. And some of my classmates, you know, at Excelsior Elementary School, some of their homes on the other street were bonned, fire bonned.

45
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:18,000
But I can remember something sticks out in my mind about a Badcock Furniture. And I used to think that Badcock Furniture, they were bad people.

46
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:26,000
But it was like this Badcock Furniture I would hear from a child's point of view, bad cops. You didn't trust the Badcock Furniture, you know.

47
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:37,000
And I remember one morning, you know, my mom was on the porch. She was coming here. And Dr. King must have, he was staying across the street to Mr. Proctor's house.

48
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:46,000
And I don't know if he stayed there that night. All I know is he came across the street to ask my mom if she was going to participate in the rally or to marches that night.

49
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:54,000
And that I used to always think it was like a faded memory. I asked my mom when I got older. Did that actually happen because I remember it happening, you know.

50
00:07:54,000 --> 00:08:00,000
And she said it did, you know, you know, you have these faded memories, you know, you have to verify.

51
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:13,000
But as I grew older, that's about 10, 11, 12 when you had to venture off downtown. That was the only time I really experienced, you know, this segregation going into the store.

52
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:25,000
And people watching you like you, we're going to take something or steal something. And I can remember the, because everything was in walking distance downtown was not far away.

53
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:32,000
It was less than two miles, less than a mile. But I can remember the doctor's building in Flagler hospital was around the corner.

54
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:42,000
And the doctor's building on trimmer's in street, I can remember a colored sign being up on the wall when you walk through the front door.

55
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:53,000
And as you, it was right to the right. I mean, I can see that sign even now. But the memory is I can also, you know, remember it coming down.

56
00:08:53,000 --> 00:09:03,000
But we would have to go to the right and go around to the back of the doctor's office. And there was a straight hallway when you walk through the door that you could not tread.

57
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:13,000
And I was always wondering what was down that hallway, you know, that's the way I wanted to go. But the sign, the colored sign pointed to the way that I should go.

58
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:26,000
But I can remember that sign coming down. And although they painted over where that sign was, the spot where it was was still, you still could see the spot.

59
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:34,000
So when it came down, I thought, you know, and I took my sister, one of my younger sisters to the doctor, because my mom, we were working in my stepfather as well.

60
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:45,000
But I had to take her to the doctor's office because although I was a second from the oldest, I was giving a lot of responsibility, I guess, because I was, my mom always said, beyond my years.

61
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:51,000
And I remember I said, well, the sign is down. I'm going to go straight down this hallway, which was forbidden before.

62
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:57,000
And I walked down there and my little sister and we ended in the doctor's office.

63
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:05,000
And everybody looked at you as though you had a communicable disease. You know, when you walk through that door, I can just remember that feeling.

64
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:14,000
But I went to the front, put my name down for my sister as she needed to see the doctor and we sat down.

65
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:21,000
And to my surprise, they called us first. And I thought, oh, great, we won't have to wait that long.

66
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:29,000
But then they marched us back through that office back to the backside where we used to come in the back.

67
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:39,000
And if I followed your time and correct, if you're 10 or 12 at the time, this is well past, of course, the passage of the Civil Rights Act.

68
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:41,000
This is 66, 67, 68.

69
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:42,000
Yes.

70
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:49,000
Yes. I couldn't remember the exact year, but I do remember the sign when it came down.

71
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:55,000
As I grew older, you don't understand from a child's point of view what is happening all around you.

72
00:10:55,000 --> 00:11:04,000
Yet I remember being in the fifth grade and I completed my fifth grade year at Excelsior Elementary School Elementary School.

73
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:12,000
And in the sixth grade, we had to go, it was forced integration. So our school closed down and we had to go to our street school.

74
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:16,000
And I could recall the teachers not wanting to teach you.

75
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:21,000
You know, it was in the kids not wanting to sit by you.

76
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:28,000
But I felt good about myself because I was not, you know, I guess I had some good self-esteem.

77
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:32,000
And I was a smart, you know, the braggest fact.

78
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:41,000
You know, I was a smart child. I probably would have been valedictorian if the school's remained black, you know, or salutatorial of my class.

79
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:50,000
But I can remember going to be in force to go to the schools and we had to fight.

80
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:56,000
It looked like it was a non-violence. We had to fight even to eat, you know.

81
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:59,000
The teachers didn't want to teach you.

82
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:09,000
And you felt a sense of a second-class citizen which I never felt being in the area of Lincolnville when it was segregated, you know.

83
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:12,000
But I didn't like that feeling.

84
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:22,000
And so even through our teen years going to the junior high school, the junior high school didn't even have a cafeteria.

85
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:25,000
So you had to walk back to Orange Street just to eat.

86
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:31,000
And the white kids were form a line, you know, to prevent you from going to eat your lunch.

87
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:40,000
So it was a lot of violence back then. I remember in the teens, you know, in the junior high in the high school.

88
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:45,000
It wasn't non-violence. You know, people were fighting.

89
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:50,000
Just fighting just to, like I said, just to eat lunch, you know.

90
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:55,000
Because you were not wanted and they made you feel that way. You were not wanted at those schools.

91
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:00,000
But Lord Blessing, you know, we were able to get on and graduate even through St. Augustine High School.

92
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:08,000
But you still felt that atmosphere of not being a part of the city in which you grew up in.

93
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:11,000
My kids experienced it too, you know.

94
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:14,000
And there is an atmosphere still here in this town.

95
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:23,000
Mrs. Mrs. Cora Tyson Johnson refers to it as like a hidden vapor, you know, over this town.

96
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:31,000
But I think the Lord for the Twines, I think the Lord for Dr. Robert B. Hayling, I learned about him later in life as I grew up.

97
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:39,000
And there was an opportunity after one of my friends, Mrs. Mrs. Catherine Twine died.

98
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:44,000
She would tell us bits and pieces about the civil rights movement.

99
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:53,000
And I felt that because I lived through it, you know, the signs being up and they coming down.

100
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:04,000
But David Nolan, after her internment in 2002, he and JT Johnson from Atlanta, Georgia.

101
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:11,000
Jane Billings of Brown, she was a professor at one of the schools. I think it was Spellman in Atlanta.

102
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:16,000
David Nolan, as I said, Mrs. Mrs. Cora Tyson Johnson, Dwight.

103
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:20,000
I can't remember his last name. Dwight Hines, I believe it was.

104
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:23,000
Sandra Parks, they all met at a restaurant.

105
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:25,000
South Seas over on the island.

106
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:33,000
And they discussed the upcoming 40th anniversary of the civil rights movement of Sinagasni.

107
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:38,000
And David Nolan, who is a local historian, asked me to put on my thinking cap.

108
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:44,000
They come up with some ideas of how we could commemorate or celebrate this event.

109
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:49,000
And so when I got that email, I told my husband about it.

110
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:53,000
And he said, we'll help. We'll do what we can. So I emailed him back.

111
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:56,000
And I said, whatever you want me to do, I'll do it.

112
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:02,000
I said, we can base this celebration, this commemoration on a family reunion.

113
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:07,000
And invite all these people who have participated in the movement back to Sinagasni.

114
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:14,000
Because in 2001, we had a family, our first family reunion in which we invited people from all around the country,

115
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:18,000
you know, back to Sinagasni for a family reunion.

116
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:20,000
And David Nolan took part in that.

117
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:26,000
And I just want to mention too that we found one of my daughter did genealogy research.

118
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:33,000
And we found one of our cousins who was the ambassador of Medagascar under President Clinton's administration.

119
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:38,000
We found her all the way over in Africa, Medagascar to Allen on the side.

120
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:42,000
But it was such a wonderful time, a joyous time.

121
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:47,000
Until I thought that would be a great thing to invite these people back to hear their stories,

122
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:50,000
their incredible stories of their participation.

123
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:55,000
Because as we learned about the civil rights movement, we know a lot of them left the city.

124
00:15:55,000 --> 00:16:00,000
So Miss Mrs. Cora Tyson Johnson and I set up a meeting at the Gallimor Center.

125
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:09,000
And we put it in the paper and invited people to come for a strategic meeting to see if there was any interest in, you know, having this commemoration,

126
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:12,000
which was to take place in a couple of years.

127
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:20,000
And we were amazed that older people came out and they began to share their stories.

128
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:22,000
There were incredible stories.

129
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:25,000
Some of them were heart wrenching stories.

130
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:39,000
Some just, I mean, it was just tear jerkers hearing what the terror that these people went through during that era of the civil rights movement led by Dr. Robert B. Hayling, Dr. King.

131
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:52,000
And so from that meeting on, we decided we're going to just bring these people back to St. Augustine and invite them and sort of can tell their stories and, you know, just get together.

132
00:16:52,000 --> 00:17:02,000
And not necessarily have a joyous time but commemorate and remember and recognize what happened in St. Augustine because it was, it was hidden.

133
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:10,000
It was hidden by the power structures in [St.] Augustine who didn't want to acknowledge that something like that ever happened.

134
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:15,000
I remember one meeting we had at, it was on the Soto place.

135
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:21,000
And J.T. Johnson would come in and he flew in from Atlanta. We invited him to come.

136
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:30,000
And there was a demonstrator sitting in their audience and he said, why don't you all let sleeping dogs lie? Why bring this up again?

137
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:32,000
Just leave it alone, let it go.

138
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:39,000
And J.T. Johnson stood up and he said, it's just time to just say thank you.

139
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:44,000
And that struck me even to this day and we just wanted to say thank you.

140
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:49,000
We wanted to bring these people back and just say thank you for the sacrifices that you made for us.

141
00:17:49,000 --> 00:18:04,000
I know it probably was disappointing, you know, to some of them who fought so much, you know, to make life better for the next generation and generations after to come back and see things had not changed much here in St. Augustine.

142
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:10,000
St. Augustine at one point didn't appreciate its black history.

143
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:30,000
I learned later in life that the first free black settlement in the United States was Fort Mose, you know, and that may be know why my ancestors came so far and risked so much that come to this place of sanctuary because it was a sanctuary for blacks at one point.

144
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:36,000
Things have changed. They're not the same even now and it makes me want to cry.

145
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:52,000
It brings people tears to know that all that Dr. Robert Hayling, all that Dr. Martin Luther King did here in this town, there's something still remain the same.

146
00:18:52,000 --> 00:19:05,000
But, and I will wipe my tears away, I am so thankful, I am so grateful for the sacrifices made by these people.

147
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:14,000
I want them to know that the sacrifice was not a vain for me. I have five children, excuse me.

148
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:22,000
I have five children and we stress education that they must get a good education in order to survive in this world.

149
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:35,000
But I have a son, Zebra Lendonkin, who graduated with the engineering degree from the University of Florida, industrial engineering degree and systems engineering, got a bachelor's degree.

150
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:41,000
And he came back to this town seeking a job and could not find a job.

151
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:51,000
He was even qualified to treat, to teach geometry, trigonometry, all of these high math courses, but he could not get a job in this city.

152
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:59,000
So he went back to school and got his bachelor's degree and building and construction and still couldn't get a job in this city.

153
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:11,000
He wrote something that really touched my heart not too long ago and put it on online that the city that he loved will never be the city that he will come back to ever again.

154
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:18,000
And this has been, this has been an norm for a lot of black people here in this city.

155
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:23,000
I'm just going to tell the truth about it.

156
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:31,000
Saint Augustine, Florida, Florida needs to change and the change is going to come and I don't know who's going to make those changes.

157
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:34,000
Maybe be the young people who come back to make changes here.

158
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:41,000
But about the civil rights movement and the 40th accord, it has been a pleasure.

159
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:54,000
It has been an honor these last eight years to bring recognition and honor to these folks to enlighten the public about what happened here.

160
00:20:54,000 --> 00:21:05,000
The struggles that these people faced just for the basic human rights.

161
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:14,000
I just thank God our organization, the 40th accord, there are no paid employees. Nobody gets paid.

162
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:18,000
And for a number of years, we weren't even funded, you know.

163
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:31,000
But in the Northrop Grumman incorporation, thank God, they decided to give us a chance and they funded 30 historic civil rights markers in and around the city.

164
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:57,000
And I thank God that some of the city officials allowed this to happen and some private citizens offered and gave us permission to put these markers, these historic markers in their yard to tell the stories because there are many, there are numerous stories of the sacrifices made by just local citizens and those who came from afar, you know, to help with this movement.

165
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:10,000
And I'm just glad to be a part of bringing recognition to people like Dr. Robert Hayling, the St. Augustine Foot Soldiers, Audrey Nell Hamilton, it was in Joanne Anderson, Elmer.

166
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:26,000
We have a lady who's a hundred, she'll be a hundred and seven years old this year who gave her name is Mrs. Mrs. Reena Ayers, who gave lodging and food to the many demonstrators who came from the North, to attorneys who came from the North to defend them in the courts.

167
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:40,000
And it is our hope that this knowledge of this American history is known not only in the United States but afar as well around the world.

168
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:55,000
So if anybody watches this 50, 60, 70 years from today, they'll know that there was some great people that walked among us, angels I call them.

169
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:01,000
And their sacrifices will not go in vain.

170
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:09,000
And I want my children to know about it, my grandchildren to know, I want everyone to know what happened here in St. Augustine, Florida.

171
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:24,000
Let me ask you kind of a hard question, which is, what are the things that haven't changed that are the problems now as you line them up and see them in the city around you?

172
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:30,000
There are not a lot of jobs and opportunities for blacks here in St. Augustine.

173
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:37,000
If you went up and down the streets, you probably wouldn't even find, you probably count on your hand the black businesses and I doubt if one hand would cover it.

174
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:40,000
There was a loss of jobs.

175
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:43,000
If one hand wouldn't cover it, probably.

176
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:51,000
Yeah, one hand probably wouldn't cover those jobs. I mean, you know, those businesses.

177
00:23:52,000 --> 00:24:04,000
There's not a lot of blacks in the city government. It's not a lot of blacks even in any type of administration and power here in St. Augustine, to me, in St. John's County.

178
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:11,000
And a lot of people have just left the city. The young people have left and I don't know if they will return.

179
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:12,000
Like your son.

180
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:14,000
Like your son, as well.

181
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:23,000
But he doesn't live that far away. He's right over in Jacksonville. And his wife is a professional, an internal medicine.

182
00:24:23,000 --> 00:24:30,000
She has a Indian internal medicine. I have a daughter who has a doctorate degree in physical therapy.

183
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:36,000
But she's here in St. Augustine. She has a job now, but she's looking to go elsewhere.

184
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:45,000
She just came back here a few months ago from Ocala, Florida. And she's thinking about moving to her wife for a little while and, you know, just seeing the United States.

185
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:56,000
But if we can get job opportunities back here, I think there would be a change made in St. Augustine.

186
00:24:56,000 --> 00:25:03,000
Tell me, I'm interested in the reaction to the placement of the Freedom Trail markers.

187
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:08,000
And the range of reaction, maybe, is the right way to ask the question.

188
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:16,000
Well, they're like, as the ambassador, young said, they're like, weeds growing up.

189
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:22,000
I guess the atmosphere now is better than it used to be. I couldn't even say two or three years ago.

190
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:27,000
There is a demand to know about the history.

191
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:33,000
There are tourists coming in asking about the civil rights movement.

192
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:44,000
Some didn't even know it was a movement here. When they heard about it through, I guess, Crossing in St. Augustine and Ambassador to Young did, that brought a lot of recognition to the movement.

193
00:25:45,000 --> 00:26:03,000
Some didn't even know Dr. King even came. But I think now with the new city manager, you know, the attitudes with Ambassador Andrew Young come in that attitude has changed a little bit.

194
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:13,000
And I guess once history that was covered up by the city is now being embraced because they see, and I'm thinking, because it's the money maker, you know.

195
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:20,000
And I believe the dollar is the revenue that can be generated is the driving factor.

196
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:21,000
Do you think now?

197
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:31,000
Do you think that that's ultimately the calculation that motivated the city's willingness to place the trail markers and the

198
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:41,000
foot soldiers monuments rather than a more sort of a deeper moral transformation? I mean, I know you can't really know the answer for sure, but

199
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:48,000
Well, the foot soldiers monument, that was a private venture.

200
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:49,000
Yeah.

201
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:53,000
I mean, the city took credit after it was, you know, the money was there.

202
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:00,000
But at least they sort of, if they weren't welcoming, at least they didn't do what all that they could have to stop it from happening.

203
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:01,000
I can say that, I guess.

204
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:05,000
I think the wheels were turning and it just wasn't going to stop.

205
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:06,000
Yeah.

206
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:08,000
I mean, people were going to keep coming, you know.

207
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:15,000
And like I said, a lot of people that gave us permission were private citizens to put those markers on in their yards.

208
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:16,000
Right.

209
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:22,000
But the city, I guess attitudes have changed somewhat.

210
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:31,000
And, you know, with the Ambassador Andrew Young coming back here and previewing his movie, that, that, I mean, really thanks took off after that.

211
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:33,000
Just more exposure.

212
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:35,000
Yes, very much.

213
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:37,000
It was a national exposure.

214
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:40,000
How do you evaluate the motives of Northrop Grumman?

215
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:57,000
Well, you know what, I just, I'm going to attribute that to just God's blessings because I have wrote a letter to the management there asking for funding, you know, to help with this commemoration, the recognition services that we were having.

216
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:00,000
And it fell in the right hands.

217
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:01,000
That's what I say.

218
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:19,000
And Lord, just blessed, and it opened up their hearts because the history shows that Fertile Hill, the company that was previously there, they were not very friendly to the civil rights demonstrators or blacks that were employed there.

219
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:22,000
And I, I trivited to the people coming from the North.

220
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:28,000
You know, the attitudes were not the same as those that were here in the South.

221
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:37,000
We're back after a brief, just a very brief pause to change recording tracks.

222
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:40,000
Okay.

223
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:46,000
I'm just talking, let me ask you for, you've been so patient to accommodate our crazy schedule today.

224
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:53,000
And the, the, the history runs so broad and deep, it's, it's hard to, to have just a relatively small amount of time.

225
00:28:53,000 --> 00:29:08,000
But I want to ask you, are there other things when you tell this story and help people understand St. Augustine, other things that we should spend some time talking about themes, episodes, incidents?

226
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:18,000
Well, St. Augustine, I'm telling you, it is a great little town. I mean, I always thought it was a wonderful place to raise a family because it's quiet.

227
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:25,000
You know, if the big one being in New York City, you know, just visited, I would not want to raise kids in, in, in New York City.

228
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:34,000
St. Augustine was a, is a quiet town, a peaceful town. But as, uh, Hank Thomas said, it is paternalistic.

229
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:39,000
It's so, we need caring for, you know, as, so we can't take care of ourselves, you know.

230
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:43,000
But, um, it's a tourist town.

231
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:50,000
And, um, we need to bring some more industry into the city.

232
00:29:50,000 --> 00:30:01,000
I could see the city of St. Augustine remaining old and, you know, historic, but the county itself needs to open up to industry where people will come back.

233
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:07,000
And blacks will be, it'll be a place that they can come, raise their families, like it used to be.

234
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:10,000
I would like to see it like it used to be.

235
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:17,000
It was good growing up in Lincolnville. It was good growing up in St. Augustine. And there were thousands of black people here.

236
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:26,000
They have just taken flight out of this place. And I think something needs to be done to draw the people back.

237
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:29,000
What's next for 40th accord?

238
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:39,000
Well, we have, um, an upcoming speaker. We always commemorate the anniversary of the Signing of the Civil Rights Act.

239
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:48,000
In this past July, we had Dr. Dorothy Cotton come. She was our keynote speaker. And I guess speaker was Sonja Plummer.

240
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:53,000
She was a granddaughter of one of the Civil Rights activists here, Reverend Goldie Eubanks.

241
00:30:53,000 --> 00:31:02,000
She comes July 2012. We have, uh, Taylor Branch coming.

242
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:13,000
That's, that will be our signature event. The, uh, and we do freedom trail tours from time to time to educate the public and tourists who come who want to know about the history.

243
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:19,000
And you help, you help, uh, with the whole series of, um, materials and training for school teachers?

244
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:29,000
Yes, we've done two workshops in the, uh, we got permission from the superintendent of schools and we did two workshops for the Teachers of St. John's County.

245
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:38,000
And it was wonderful. And we had one at St. Augustine High School. Dr. Robert Hayling. We had brought in Miss Lillian, Twine Robeson.

246
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:52,000
Uh, There were numerous speakers to share their stories with the teachers. We put together a, a workbook, um, of civil rights activities, pictures, documents for the teachers.

247
00:31:52,000 --> 00:32:03,000
The first year, an Northrop Grumman funded it and the, I guess two years later, we did it again. And we put them on, you know, the, the workbook on the CD.

248
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:11,000
But funding has been an issue, you know, for the 40th of cord and getting programs done because it wasn't a popular subject.

249
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:21,000
And we saw it State Federal, you know, CD State and County Federal funds, but never were approved. If it wasn't for the Northrop Grumman, you know,

250
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:33,000
the story would not have gotten out. So, um, but our, I guess our long term goal is to establish a civil rights museum here in St. Augustine.

251
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:42,000
That is, is not just the 40th of cord. We have, uh, the 40th of cord started an organization, uh, I guess a committee.

252
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:50,000
And we had a meeting and they decided to come up from under the umbrella of a cord because it's such a big adventure.

253
00:32:50,000 --> 00:33:00,000
And we have the chairman, Richard Burton out of Jacksonville, who was a national NAACP board member. He's our chair, JT Johnson Co. Chair.

254
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:15,000
We have the, um, President Flagler Hospital on that committee, the mayor's on that committee. And, um, we're looking by 2014 to have something up and running.

255
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:30,000
Not the multimillion-dollar facility that Ambassador Andrew Young has, uh, great hopes of raising funds for, but something to celebrate and commemorate the 50th anniversary of the Civil Rights Act in St. Augustine.

256
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:40,000
Yeah. Yeah. Well, it's just been a great honor and privilege. I really want to thank you. And, um, it'll be really great to watch all those plans move forward. So thank you for all that you've done and all that you're doing.

257
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:41,000
Thank you.

258
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:44,000
And thanks for joining us today. Thank you.

259
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:56,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

